WEBVTT

00:00:02.400 --> 00:00:13.200
<v Teacher>So we've seen how <b>me</b> can mean <i>me</i>, <i>to me</i> or <i>myself</i>, and <b>te</b> can mean <i>you</i>, <i>to you</i> or <i>yourself</i>.

00:00:13.620 --> 00:00:18.980
<v Teacher>And <b>nos</b> can mean <i>us</i>, <i>to us</i>, or <i>ourselves</i>.

00:00:18.980 --> 00:00:23.380
<v Teacher>So we want to resist the temptation to translate this <i>to</i>.

00:00:23.380 --> 00:00:26.820
<v Teacher>So for example, <i>he speaks to me</i>,

00:00:27.140 --> 00:00:34.260
<v Teacher>we don't need this <i>to</i> because <b>me</b>, <b>me</b>, can mean <i>me</i>, <i>to me</i> or <i>myself</i>.

00:00:34.260 --> 00:00:37.620
<v Teacher>So we want to resist the temptation to translate that <i>to</i>.

00:00:38.180 --> 00:00:44.339
<v Teacher>So how do you say <i>he speaks to me</i> or <i>he's speaking to me</i>?

00:00:46.260 --> 00:00:48.180
<v Student><b>Habla me</b>. Sorry, <b>me habla</b>.

00:00:48.180 --> 00:00:53.019
<v Teacher>Yeah, don't let that <i>to</i> confuse you about the position it should go. It's still going before, <b>me habla</b>.

00:00:53.019 --> 00:00:56.219
<v Teacher><i>They speak to me</i>:

00:00:56.219 --> 00:00:57.420
<v Student><b>Me hablan</b>.

00:00:57.420 --> 00:00:57.899
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:57.899 --> 00:01:04.780
<v Teacher>If you want to say they speak to me about it, you can just say they speak me it in Spanish.

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:07.360
<v Student><b>Me lo hablan</b>.

00:01:07.360 --> 00:01:09.040
<v Teacher><b>Me lo hablan</b>. Very good. <i>They're speaking to me about it</i>.

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:17.680
<v Teacher>So this <i>to</i> and this <i>about</i>, we notice Spanish tends not to need these words as much as English does.

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:21.200
<v Teacher>For example, <i>to buy</i> was <b>comprar</b>, <b>comprar</b>.

00:01:22.560 --> 00:01:23.520
<v Student><b>Comprar</b>.

00:01:23.520 --> 00:01:24.479
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:24.479 --> 00:01:32.500
<v Teacher>So this <b>me</b> other than <i>to me</i> can be <i>for me</i>, <i>from me</i>, we don't really need these words.

00:01:32.500 --> 00:01:39.060
<v Teacher>So for example, if we want to say <i>he buys it for me</i> we can just say <i>he buys me it</i>.

00:01:39.360 --> 00:01:42.400
<v Teacher>So <b>comprar</b> is <i>to buy</i>. <i>He buys it for me</i>, <i>he buys me it</i>:

00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:49.000
<v Student><b>Me lo compra</b>.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:50.520
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Me lo compra</b>.

00:01:50.600 --> 00:01:56.440
<v Teacher>So here we see <b>me</b> is like <i>for me</i> here. But it's just <b>me</b>, we're just using <b>me</b>.

00:01:56.440 --> 00:02:01.080
<v Teacher><i>I buy it for you</i>, speaking informally. <i>I buy it for you</i>:

00:02:02.100 --> 00:02:03.540
<v Student><b>Te lo compro</b>.

00:02:03.540 --> 00:02:06.100
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Te lo compro</b>.

00:02:06.100 --> 00:02:10.500
<v Teacher>Now, if you want to say <i>shall I buy it for you</i>,

00:02:10.500 --> 00:02:15.300
<v Teacher><i>shall</i> in English, all it's doing really is just making it a question.

00:02:15.300 --> 00:02:16.900
<v Teacher><i>Shall I buy it for you</i>?

00:02:16.900 --> 00:02:20.740
<v Teacher>So in Spanish, just make it sound like a question.

00:02:20.740 --> 00:02:22.880
<v Student>¿<b>Te lo compro</b>?

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:25.760
<v Teacher>Yeah! ¿<b>Te lo compro</b>? <i>Shall I buy it for you</i>?

00:02:25.760 --> 00:02:29.200
<v Teacher>Now this could actually even mean <i>from you</i>.

00:02:29.200 --> 00:02:31.200
<v Teacher><i>Shall I buy it from you</i>?

00:02:31.200 --> 00:02:34.640
<v Teacher>So by the context we'll understand the difference.

00:02:34.660 --> 00:02:42.180
<v Teacher>Maybe you will hear if you travel to a Spanish-speaking country, people say, buy me selling things in the street

00:02:42.320 --> 00:02:45.040
<v Teacher>Buy me something is what you will hear.

00:02:45.040 --> 00:02:50.400
<v Teacher>And they're probably not asking you to buy them something, but to buy something from them.

00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:56.960
<v Teacher>And it's understood and we don't really need to use these words like from or for most of the time.

00:02:57.460 --> 00:03:01.300
<v Teacher><i>To do</i> was <b>hacer</b>, <b>hacer</b>. How would you say <i>do you want to do</i> (speaking informally)?

00:03:06.860 --> 00:03:09.180
<v Student><b>Hacer</b> is an irregular verb.

00:03:09.260 --> 00:03:10.540
<v Teacher>It doesn't matter, does it? <i>Do you want to do</i>?:

00:03:12.620 --> 00:03:13.420
<v Student>Ah!

00:03:13.420 --> 00:03:15.739
<v Student>¿<b>Quieres hacer</b>?

00:03:15.739 --> 00:03:16.540
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:16.540 --> 00:03:18.540
<v Teacher><i>Do you want to do it</i>?

00:03:18.540 --> 00:03:20.840
<v Student>¿<b>Quieres hacerlo</b>?

00:03:20.840 --> 00:03:21.319
<v Teacher>Good. ¿<b>Quieres hacerlo</b>?

00:03:21.319 --> 00:03:25.480
<v Teacher>Now how do you think you would say: <i>do you want to do it for me</i>?:

00:03:27.300 --> 00:03:28.980
<v Student>¿<b>Me lo quieres hacer</b>?

00:03:28.980 --> 00:03:29.860
<v Teacher>Yes.

00:03:29.860 --> 00:03:35.700
<v Teacher>¿<b>Me lo quieres hacer</b>? So, we are not using the word <i>for</i> for <i>for</i>. We don't need it in Spanish, it's understood.

00:03:35.700 --> 00:03:40.420
<v Teacher><i>Do you want to do it for me</i>? ¿<b>Me lo quieres hacer</b>? ¿<b>Quieres hacérmelo</b>? Good.

00:03:40.420 --> 00:03:52.040
<v Teacher>The kitchen in Spanish is <b>la cocina</b>, /la cosina/, or in most of Spain, /la cothina/. <b>La cocina</b>.

00:03:52.040 --> 00:03:53.320
<v Student><b>La cocina</b>.

00:03:53.320 --> 00:03:58.099
<v Teacher>And <i>to cook</i> is <b>cocinar</b>. You just make a verb from <b>cocina</b>, <b>cocinar</b>.

00:03:58.099 --> 00:04:05.140
<v Teacher>Actually this is where we get <i>concoction</i>, <i>concoction</i> from in English, "with cooking".

00:04:05.140 --> 00:04:10.440
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>I cook</i> from <b>cocinar</b>?

00:04:10.440 --> 00:04:11.560
<v Student><b>Cocino</b>.

00:04:11.560 --> 00:04:12.040
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:12.040 --> 00:04:17.720
<v Teacher>How do you say <i>he cooks</i> or <i>she cooks</i> or <i>it cooks</i> or <b>usted</b>, <i>you</i> (formal) <i>cook</i>?

00:04:18.660 --> 00:04:19.700
<v Student><b>Cocina</b>.

00:04:19.700 --> 00:04:20.100
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:20.100 --> 00:04:22.340
<v Teacher><i>You</i> (informal)?

00:04:22.340 --> 00:04:23.380
<v Student><b>Cocinas</b>.

00:04:23.380 --> 00:04:23.780
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:23.780 --> 00:04:28.500
<v Teacher>And with emphasis or clarification if you want to use the word for <i>you</i>?

00:04:29.040 --> 00:04:29.919
<v Student><b>Usted</b>.

00:04:29.919 --> 00:04:32.400
<v Teacher>But this is informal, <b>cocinas</b>.

00:04:32.400 --> 00:04:33.520
<v Student>Ah sorry!

00:04:33.520 --> 00:04:34.880
<v Student><b>Tú cocinas</b>.

00:04:34.880 --> 00:04:36.960
<v Teacher><b>Tú cocinas</b>. Good. <i>They cook</i> or <i>you guys</i>?

00:04:36.960 --> 00:04:41.600
<v Student><b>Cocinan</b>.

00:04:41.600 --> 00:04:42.160
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:42.160 --> 00:04:47.680
<v Teacher>What if you wanted to use the word for <i>they</i>, to emphasize or to clarify?

00:04:47.680 --> 00:04:49.600
<v Student><b>Ellos cocinan</b>.

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:51.520
<v Teacher><b>Ellos cocinan</b>. Good.

00:04:51.520 --> 00:04:53.960
<v Teacher>Or <b>ellas</b> if it's a female group.

00:04:53.960 --> 00:04:59.800
<v Teacher>Or if you wanted to say <i>you guys are cooking</i> with the emphasis or the clarification?

00:05:01.620 --> 00:05:03.780
<v Student><b>Ustedes cocinan</b>.

00:05:03.780 --> 00:05:05.699
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Ustedes cocinan</b>.

00:05:05.699 --> 00:05:07.940
<v Teacher>And <i>we cook</i>? What is <i>we cook</i>?

00:05:07.940 --> 00:05:10.259
<v Student><b>Cocinamos</b>.

00:05:10.259 --> 00:05:10.580
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:10.580 --> 00:05:13.860
<v Teacher>And with the emphasis or the clarification?

00:05:14.580 --> 00:05:16.740
<v Student><b>Nosotros cocinamos</b>.

00:05:16.740 --> 00:05:19.060
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Nosotros cocinamos</b>. Good.

00:05:19.060 --> 00:05:22.420
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>I can</i>?

00:05:22.420 --> 00:05:26.100
<v Teacher>How is <i>I can</i>, related to <i>power</i>?

00:05:26.540 --> 00:05:27.500
<v Student><b>Puedo</b>.

00:05:27.500 --> 00:05:28.860
<v Teacher><b>Puedo</b>. Good. And <i>he can</i>:

00:05:28.860 --> 00:05:32.139
<v Student><b>Puede</b>.

00:05:32.139 --> 00:05:34.139
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Puede</b>. And <i>you can</i> (informal):

00:05:34.139 --> 00:05:36.780
<v Student><b>Puedes</b>.

00:05:36.780 --> 00:05:38.060
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:38.060 --> 00:05:39.500
<v Teacher><i>Can you cook</i>?:

00:05:39.500 --> 00:05:41.699
<v Student>¿<b>Puedes cocinar</b>?

00:05:41.699 --> 00:05:42.340
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:42.340 --> 00:05:45.460
<v Teacher><i>Can you cook something for me</i>?

00:05:45.460 --> 00:05:47.620
<v Teacher>So what was the word for <i>something</i>?

00:05:47.980 --> 00:05:48.780
<v Student><b>Algo</b>.

00:05:48.780 --> 00:05:49.180
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:49.180 --> 00:05:53.660
<v Teacher>How do you think you are gonna say this in Spanish? <i>Can you cook something for me</i>?:

00:05:57.120 --> 00:05:58.720
<v Student>¿<b>Me puedes cocinar algo</b>?

00:05:58.720 --> 00:06:01.280
<v Teacher>Good. ¿<b>Me puedes cocinar algo</b>?

00:06:01.280 --> 00:06:04.400
<v Teacher>¿<b>Puedes cocinarme algo</b>? Either way.

00:06:04.400 --> 00:06:08.400
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>I have cooked</i>? <i>I have cooked</i>:

00:06:09.180 --> 00:06:10.699
<v Student><b>He cocinado</b>.

00:06:10.699 --> 00:06:12.860
<v Teacher><b>He cocinado</b>. Good.

00:06:12.860 --> 00:06:21.720
<v Teacher>So we said that this tense of <i>have cooked</i>, <i>I have cooked</i> instead of <i>I cooked</i>, we can use it more in Spanish than in English.

00:06:21.720 --> 00:06:26.760
<v Teacher>So for example in English it sounds much more natural to say <i>I cooked at 6 o'clock</i>,

00:06:26.760 --> 00:06:31.560
<v Teacher>but in Spanish it's not a problem to say <i>I have cooked at 6 o'clock</i>.

00:06:31.560 --> 00:06:41.820
<v Teacher>So, <i>at 6 o'clock</i> is <b>a las seis</b>. What you actually mean when you say <b>a las seis</b> is <b>a las seis horas</b>. "At the six hours".

00:06:41.820 --> 00:06:46.300
<v Teacher>A little bit like in English when you say "at sixteen hundred hours".

00:06:46.300 --> 00:06:48.060
<v Teacher><b>A las seis</b>.

00:06:48.060 --> 00:06:54.380
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>I have cooked at 6 o'clock</i>? <i>I cooked at 6 o'clock</i>:

00:06:54.520 --> 00:06:57.240
<v Student><b>He cocinado a las seis</b>.

00:06:57.240 --> 00:07:05.199
<v Teacher>Good. <b>He cocinado a las seis</b>. <i>I have cooked at six o'clock</i>. <i>I cooked at six o'clock</i>. Good.

00:07:05.199 --> 00:07:10.240
<v Teacher>The word for <i>eight</i> in Spanish is <b>ocho</b>. <b>Ocho</b>.

00:07:10.240 --> 00:07:10.960
<v Student><b>Ocho</b>.

00:07:10.960 --> 00:07:17.120
<v Teacher><b>Ocho</b>. We have this similar root in <i>octagon</i>, you know, a shape with eight sides.

00:07:17.120 --> 00:07:30.180
<v Teacher>Or <i>octopus</i>, which has eight legs. Or in <i>October</i>, which, well now it's the tenth month, in the Roman calendar there were only ten months and October was month number eight.

00:07:30.180 --> 00:07:32.880
<v Teacher>So, <b>ocho</b>, <i>eight</i>.

00:07:32.880 --> 00:07:38.160
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>we have cooked at eight o'clock</i>? <i>We have cooked at eight o'clock</i>:

00:07:39.360 --> 00:07:43.199
<v Student><b>Hemos cocinado a las ocho</b>.

00:07:43.199 --> 00:07:47.199
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Hemos cocinado a las ocho</b>.

00:07:47.199 --> 00:07:51.840
<v Teacher>The word for <i>nine</i> in Spanish is <b>nueve</b>.

00:07:51.840 --> 00:07:59.060
<v Student><b>Nueve</b>.

00:07:59.060 --> 00:08:00.880
<v Teacher>We can see in November, which used to be the ninth month. The o splits into <i>ue</i>, <b>nueve</b>.

00:08:00.880 --> 00:08:02.640
<v Teacher>And we have the same with <i>ten</i>.

00:08:02.640 --> 00:08:06.960
<v Teacher><i>Ten</i> is <b>diez</b> or /dieth/ in most of Spain. <b>Diez</b>.

00:08:07.840 --> 00:08:11.520
<v Teacher>What does that sound like, if you go back to our calendar?

00:08:11.940 --> 00:08:12.819
<v Student>December?

00:08:12.819 --> 00:08:20.819
<v Teacher><i>December</i>, which used to be the tenth month and of course again an example of splitting. <i>Dec</i> to <b>diez</b>.

00:08:20.819 --> 00:08:28.080
<v Teacher><b>Quedar</b> in Spanish, <b>quedar</b>, means <i>to remain</i>, or <i>to be left over</i>

00:08:28.080 --> 00:08:34.099
<v Teacher>and it actually has quite a few other meanings as well, it's quite a flexible verb, <b>quedar</b>.

00:08:34.099 --> 00:08:40.979
<v Teacher>But for now, <i>to remain</i> or <i>to be left over</i>. <i>Q-u-e-d-a-r</i>. <b>Quedar</b>.

00:08:40.979 --> 00:08:45.060
<v Teacher>And <i>q-u</i> in Spanish is always a <i>k</i> sound.

00:08:45.060 --> 00:08:49.980
<v Teacher>You must resist any temptation to pronounce /qwedar/, if you were to read this.

00:08:49.980 --> 00:08:54.060
<v Teacher>The word <b>que</b>, the word for <i>what</i> that we learned is spelled <i>q-u-e</i>.

00:08:54.060 --> 00:08:57.420
<v Teacher><b>Quiero</b> is spelled <i>q-u-i-e-r-o</i>.

00:08:57.420 --> 00:09:00.540
<v Teacher>So <i>q-u</i> this combination is always a <i>k</i>.

00:09:00.540 --> 00:09:03.760
<v Teacher><b>Quedar</b> means <i>to remain</i>.

00:09:03.760 --> 00:09:10.720
<v Teacher>So in Spanish if you want to say <i>I stay</i> actually you say <i>I remain myself</i>.

00:09:10.720 --> 00:09:13.440
<v Teacher>This is the way you say <i>I stay</i> in Spanish.

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:18.080
<v Teacher>So we start with <i>remain</i> which is <b>quedar</b>. So how do you say <i>I remain</i>?

00:09:19.140 --> 00:09:20.020
<v Student><b>Quiedo</b>.

00:09:20.020 --> 00:09:23.220
<v Teacher>It doesn't split here but good for trying.

00:09:23.220 --> 00:09:24.020
<v Student><b>Quedo</b>?

00:09:24.020 --> 00:09:24.740
<v Teacher><b>Quedo</b>.

00:09:24.740 --> 00:09:26.900
<v Teacher><i>I remain myself</i>?

00:09:27.300 --> 00:09:28.180
<v Student><b>Me quedo</b>.

00:09:28.180 --> 00:09:31.620
<v Teacher><b>Me quedo</b>. This means <i>I stay</i>. <b>Me quedo</b>.

00:09:31.620 --> 00:09:36.820
<v Teacher><i>Until</i>, <i>until</i> in Spanish is <b>hasta</b>. <b>Hasta</b>. <i>H-a-s-t-a</i>.

00:09:36.820 --> 00:09:43.380
<v Teacher>You may have heard <b>hasta la vista</b>. <i>Until the view</i>, literally <i>until the seeing</i>, <i>until we see each other</i>. <b>Hasta la vista</b>.

00:09:43.380 --> 00:09:53.640
<v Teacher>So now you can say <i>I am staying here until ten o'clock</i>. So let's divide it up. <i>I am staying here</i>, <i>I remain myself here</i>:

00:09:53.640 --> 00:09:59.000
<v Student><b>Me quedo aquí</b>.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:06.140
<v Teacher><i>Until</i>?

00:10:06.140 --> 00:10:10.380
<v Student><b>Hasta</b>.

00:10:10.380 --> 00:10:13.260
<v Teacher><i>Ten o'clock</i>. So—

00:10:13.260 --> 00:10:15.980
<v Student><b>Las diez</b>.

00:10:15.980 --> 00:10:19.260
<v Teacher>Yes. <b>Las diez</b>. It's literally like <b>las diez horas</b>, but you don't say <b>horas</b>. Maybe historically people said it, but not anymore.

00:10:19.260 --> 00:10:22.460
<v Teacher><b>Me quedo aquí</b>, or <b>acá</b>, <b>hasta las diez</b>. Good. <i>I am staying until ten o'clock</i>.

00:10:22.460 --> 00:10:27.720
<v Teacher>So if <b>me quedo</b>, <i>I remain myself</i> is <i>I am staying</i>, how do you think you would say <i>we are staying</i>?

00:10:27.720 --> 00:10:30.620
<v Student><b>Nos quedemos</b>.

00:10:30.620 --> 00:10:39.420
<v Teacher>Good, but now you have some vowel harmony popping in because we were concentrating on the other bit, so this mistake managed to come back.

00:10:39.420 --> 00:10:40.420
<v Student><b>Quedamos</b>?

00:10:40.420 --> 00:10:44.980
<v Teacher>Good! Because it's <b>quedar</b>. No? <b>Nos quedamos</b>. <i>We remain ourselves</i>. <i>We stay</i>.

00:10:44.980 --> 00:10:48.260
<v Teacher>So <i>we are staying until nine o'clock</i>:

00:10:48.260 --> 00:10:52.920
<v Student><b>Nos quedamos hasta las nueve</b>.

00:10:52.920 --> 00:10:56.120
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Nos quedamos hasta las nueve</b>. Very good. Very good.

00:10:56.120 --> 00:11:01.399
<v Teacher><i>You stay</i> or <i>you remain yourself</i> (speaking informally):

00:11:01.399 --> 00:11:02.560
<v Student><b>Te quedas</b>.

00:11:02.560 --> 00:11:05.519
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Te quedas</b>. <i>You are staying here</i>:

00:11:05.519 --> 00:11:08.639
<v Student><b>Te quedas aquí</b>.

00:11:08.639 --> 00:11:11.920
<v Teacher><b>Te quedas aquí</b>. <i>Are you staying here</i>?:

00:11:11.920 --> 00:11:14.819
<v Student>¿<b>Te quedas aquí</b>?

00:11:14.819 --> 00:11:18.180
<v Teacher>Good. ¿<b>Te quedas aquí</b>?

00:11:18.180 --> 00:11:21.540
<v Teacher>How would you make it emphatic now? Are YOU staying here?

00:11:21.540 --> 00:11:25.540
<v Teacher>Because this <b>te</b> is not emphatic, it is not optional.

00:11:25.540 --> 00:11:29.680
<v Teacher>You have to put this <b>me</b> in <b>me quedo</b> to get the meaning of <i>stay</i>

00:11:29.680 --> 00:11:34.880
<v Teacher>and we have to put this <b>te</b> in <b>te quedas</b> to get the meaning of <i>stay</i>.

00:11:34.880 --> 00:11:38.160
<v Teacher>But if we want to make it emphatic, what do we add?

00:11:38.600 --> 00:11:41.240
<v Student>¿<b>Tú te quedas</b>?

00:11:41.240 --> 00:11:42.440
<v Teacher>Good.

00:11:42.440 --> 00:11:46.360
<v Teacher><i>I am staying</i>, emphatic.

00:11:46.360 --> 00:11:47.959
<v Student><b>Yo me quedo</b>.

00:11:47.959 --> 00:11:50.600
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Yo me quedo</b>. Good. <i>We are staying</i>:

00:11:50.600 --> 00:11:55.540
<v Student><b>Nos quedamos</b>.

